  <datafield tag="500" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">Richard Davis Webb writes to Anne Warren Weston: &quot;I am never more disposed to hold up my head and feel as if I had a little right to be conceited than when one of your faction writes me.&quot; Webb likes Anne W. Weston&apos;s report of the bazaar. He explains the reason for charging freight against the Boston society: &quot;We are a very poor people &amp; the older I grow the more entirely I am sure of it.&quot; He discusses James Haughton in relation to temperance and to abolition. Haughton intends &quot;to countenance Dr. [Orville] Dewey in his new born zeal for the cause.&quot; Webb agrees that Haughton is a saint, but insists &quot;that he is nevertheless a terrible proser both as an author and an orator.&quot; Webb wishes that he had news of the Anne W. Weston&apos;s &quot;French sisters&quot; and of Wendell Phillips. The best that Richard D. Webb has lately read or heard (on the cause) is &quot;a sermon from [Thomas Wentworth] Higginson a Unitarian minister.&quot;</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="500" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">Also with the same Call No. Ms.A.9.2 v.24, p.61, is an account of expenses on behalf of the Boston Ladies Anti-Slavery Society, with a note by Richard Davis Webb to Maria Weston Chapman, Dublin, Feb., 2, 1849. Richard D. Webb requests Robert F. Walcutt to pay Henry C. Wright a sum, which he is to charge Maria W. Chapman. On the verso, there is a receipt signed by Henry C. Wright, and these notations: &quot;Boston, Feb. 26, 1849. Rec&apos;d the written balance of [pounds] 6.10--($31.20).&quot; And on &quot;27 Feb. 1849-- P[aye]d $75/100 for bring&apos;g boxes from 294 Wash&apos;n St. to 21 Cornhill. Rec&apos;d by Mr. May, 2nd Mar. 1849.&quot;</subfield>
  </datafield>
